\par\pard\plain \ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24\b0 Hacker argues that these are indeed problems, only not empirical ones. They are conceptual problems and puzzlements that are to be dissolved or resolved by logico-linguistic analysis. It follows that scientific inquiry (learning more facts about humans or the world) does not help to resolve them anymore than discoveries in physics can help to prove a mathematical theorem. His 2003 book "Philosophical Foundations of Neuroscience", co-authored with neuroscientist\~}{\field{\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Max_Bennett_(scientist)"}{\fldrslt\f0\fs24\b0 Max Bennett}}{\f0\fs24\b0 , contains an exposition of these views, and critiques of the ideas of many contemporary neuroscientists and philosophers, including\~}{\field{\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Francis_Crick"}{\fldrslt\f0\fs24\b0 Francis Crick}}{\f0\fs24\b0 ,\~}{\field{\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Antonio_Damasio"}{\fldrslt\f0\fs24\b0 Antonio Damasio}}{\f0\fs24\b0 ,\~}{\field{\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Daniel_Dennett"}{\fldrslt\f0\fs24\b0 Daniel Dennett}}{\f0\fs24\b0 ,\~}{\field{\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/John_Searle"}{\fldrslt\f0\fs24\b0 John Searle}}{\f0\fs24\b0 , and others.}{ }
